@flexiarg coordination/task-shape-validation
@title Task Shape Validation (G5)
@keywords gate, validation, task, schema, reject, boundary
@audience coordination maintainers, futon3b builders
@tone formal-analytic
@references [futon-theory/error-hierarchy futon-theory/stop-the-line]

! conclusion:
  If you want coordination to be auditable and repeatable, gate execution on a minimal well-typed task specification and reject malformed tasks with gate attribution.

  + context: A coordination pipeline must not accept "do stuff" inputs; it must accept a task with mission binding and success criteria.
  + IF:
    you want multiple agents and tools to execute work safely

  + HOWEVER:
    accepting underspecified tasks makes later evidence unverifiable and failures ambiguous

  + THEN:
    validate the task shape at the boundary (G5) and reject with structured errors carrying `:gate/id` and `:error/key`

  + BECAUSE:
    early rejection is cheaper than running execution/validation on nonsense and later arguing about what was meant

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Define TaskSpec shape and enforce it for all inputs crossing the gate pipeline boundary.]

